    </aside>
    <article class="learn-content">
      <header class="page-header">
        <h1>Learn Elo</h1>
        <p class="page-intro">
          Programming doesn't have to be scary. Think of Elo like a powerful calculator: you write expressions,
          and Elo gives you results. No complex programs—just math, text, dates, and logic.
          Let's learn together, one step at a time.
        </p>
      </header>

      <section class="lesson" id="lesson-1" data-learn-progress-target="lesson">
        <div class="lesson-header">
          <h2>1. Playing with Numbers</h2>
          <button class="lesson-toggle" data-action="click->learn-progress#toggle" data-lesson="lesson-1" data-learn-progress-target="toggleBtn">
            <span class="toggle-check"></span><span class="toggle-text">Mark as complete</span>
          </button>
        </div>
        <p>
          Let's start with something familiar: math. Elo understands numbers and basic arithmetic.
          No special syntax, no tricks—just write it like you'd write it on paper.
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">2 + 3 * 4</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">(2 + 3) * 4</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">20 / 4 + 6 * 7</pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="lesson" id="lesson-2" data-learn-progress-target="lesson">
        <div class="lesson-header">
          <h2>2. Words, Words, Words</h2>
          <button class="lesson-toggle" data-action="click->learn-progress#toggle" data-lesson="lesson-2" data-learn-progress-target="toggleBtn">
            <span class="toggle-check"></span><span class="toggle-text">Mark as complete</span>
          </button>
        </div>
        <p>
          Text in Elo is called a <em>String</em>. Just wrap your words in quotes:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">'Hello, World!'</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          Want to combine strings? Use the <code>+</code> operator (think of it as gluing words together):
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">'Hello, ' + 'World!'</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          Elo has handy functions to transform text:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">upper('hello')</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">trim('  spaces  ')</pre>
        </div>
        <p class="lesson-tip">
          <strong>Keep it simple:</strong> Elo uses single quotes for all strings. No double quotes, no backticks—just one way to write text.
          See more <a href={url('/stdlib#string')}>string functions</a> in the stdlib.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="lesson" id="lesson-3" data-learn-progress-target="lesson">
        <div class="lesson-header">
          <h2>3. True or False?</h2>
          <button class="lesson-toggle" data-action="click->learn-progress#toggle" data-lesson="lesson-3" data-learn-progress-target="toggleBtn">
            <span class="toggle-check"></span><span class="toggle-text">Mark as complete</span>
          </button>
        </div>
        <p>
          Computers love yes/no questions. In Elo, we have <code>true</code> and <code>false</code>:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">5 > 3</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">10 <= 10</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          You can combine conditions with <code>and</code>, <code>or</code>, and <code>not</code>:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">true and false</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">5 > 3 or 2 == 2</pre>
        </div>
        <p class="lesson-tip">
          <strong>Real-world example:</strong> <code>age >= 18 and hasLicense</code> — Can this person drive?
          See all <a href={url('/docs#operators')}>operators</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="lesson" id="lesson-4" data-learn-progress-target="lesson">
        <div class="lesson-header">
          <h2>4. Making Decisions</h2>
          <button class="lesson-toggle" data-action="click->learn-progress#toggle" data-lesson="lesson-4" data-learn-progress-target="toggleBtn">
            <span class="toggle-check"></span><span class="toggle-text">Mark as complete</span>
          </button>
        </div>
        <p>
          Life is full of choices. Elo handles them with <code>if</code>/<code>then</code>/<code>else</code>:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">if 5 > 3 then 'yes' else 'no'</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">if 10 > 100 then 'big' else 'small'</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          Notice something? In Elo, <code>if</code> is an <em>expression</em>—it always produces a value.
          There's no "do this, then do that." Everything is about computing a result.
        </p>
        <p class="lesson-tip">
          <strong>Think spreadsheets:</strong> It's like Excel's <code>=IF(A1>10, "big", "small")</code>, but cleaner!
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="lesson" id="lesson-5" data-learn-progress-target="lesson">
        <div class="lesson-header">
          <h2>5. Naming Things</h2>
          <button class="lesson-toggle" data-action="click->learn-progress#toggle" data-lesson="lesson-5" data-learn-progress-target="toggleBtn">
            <span class="toggle-check"></span><span class="toggle-text">Mark as complete</span>
          </button>
        </div>
        <p>
          Repeating yourself is boring. Give values a name with <code>let</code>:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">let price = 100 in price * 1.21</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">let name = 'World' in 'Hello, ' + name + '!'</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          You can name multiple things:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">let width = 10, height = 5 in width * height</pre>
        </div>
        <p class="lesson-tip">
          <strong>No surprises:</strong> In Elo, names don't change. Once <code>price</code> is 100, it's always 100.
          No reassignments, no mutations, no bugs from unexpected changes. That's a feature, not a bug!
          More on <a href={url('/docs#variables')}>variables</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="lesson" id="lesson-6" data-learn-progress-target="lesson">
        <div class="lesson-header">
          <h2>6. Time Flies</h2>
          <button class="lesson-toggle" data-action="click->learn-progress#toggle" data-lesson="lesson-6" data-learn-progress-target="toggleBtn">
            <span class="toggle-check"></span><span class="toggle-text">Mark as complete</span>
          </button>
        </div>
        <p>
          Elo speaks dates and times fluently. Write them naturally:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">D2024-12-25</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">TODAY</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          The magic happens with <em>durations</em>. Want to know what's 30 days from today?
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">TODAY + P30D</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">NOW + PT2H30M</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          Extract parts of dates:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">year(TODAY)</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">month(TODAY)</pre>
        </div>
        <p class="lesson-tip">
          <strong>Pro tip:</strong> <code>P1Y2M3D</code> means "1 year, 2 months, 3 days."
          <code>PT</code> is for time: <code>PT1H30M</code> = 1 hour 30 minutes.
          Explore all <a href={url('/stdlib#temporal')}>temporal functions</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="lesson" id="lesson-7" data-learn-progress-target="lesson">
        <div class="lesson-header">
          <h2>7. Bundling Data</h2>
          <button class="lesson-toggle" data-action="click->learn-progress#toggle" data-lesson="lesson-7" data-learn-progress-target="toggleBtn">
            <span class="toggle-check"></span><span class="toggle-text">Mark as complete</span>
          </button>
        </div>
        <p>
          Real data comes in bundles. A person has a name, age, email. Elo uses <em>objects</em>:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">&#123; name: 'Alice', age: 30, city: 'Brussels' &#125;</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          Access parts with a dot:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">let person = &#123; name: 'Alice', age: 30 &#125; in person.name</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">let person = &#123; name: 'Bob', age: 25 &#125; in person.age >= 18</pre>
        </div>
        <p class="lesson-tip">
          <strong>Sounds familiar?</strong> If you've seen JSON, you've seen this.
          Elo objects work the same way. More on <a href={url('/docs#objects')}>objects</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="lesson" id="lesson-8" data-learn-progress-target="lesson">
        <div class="lesson-header">
          <h2>8. Input Data</h2>
          <button class="lesson-toggle" data-action="click->learn-progress#toggle" data-lesson="lesson-8" data-learn-progress-target="toggleBtn">
            <span class="toggle-check"></span><span class="toggle-text">Mark as complete</span>
          </button>
        </div>
        <p>
          Real programs don't just compute with literals—they work with data from the outside world.
          In Elo, external input is always available through the special <code>_</code> variable:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">_ * 2</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          When you use <code>_</code>, your expression becomes a function that takes input and produces output.
          In the playground, you can provide input data in the bottom panel as JSON.
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">_.price * _.quantity</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">_.budget * 1.21</pre>
        </div>
        <p class="lesson-tip">
          <strong>Think transformation:</strong> Every Elo expression with <code>_</code> is a data transformation.
          Input flows in, gets computed, and a result flows out. Try it in the <a href={url('/playground')}>playground</a> with the "Input Data" example!
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="lesson" id="lesson-9" data-learn-progress-target="lesson">
        <div class="lesson-header">
          <h2>9. Lists of Things</h2>
          <button class="lesson-toggle" data-action="click->learn-progress#toggle" data-lesson="lesson-9" data-learn-progress-target="toggleBtn">
            <span class="toggle-check"></span><span class="toggle-text">Mark as complete</span>
          </button>
        </div>
        <p>
          Sometimes you have multiple items: a list of prices, names, or dates.
          Elo uses <em>arrays</em> for this—just wrap items in square brackets:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">['apple', 'banana', 'cherry']</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          How many items? Use <code>length</code>:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">length([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          Arrays can hold any type—even mixed types or other arrays:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">let fruits = ['apple', 'banana'] in length(fruits)</pre>
        </div>
        <p class="lesson-tip">
          <strong>Think shopping lists:</strong> An array is just an ordered collection.
          You'll learn how to transform and filter arrays in the Advanced section!
          See all <a href={url('/stdlib#array')}>array functions</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="lesson" id="lesson-10" data-learn-progress-target="lesson">
        <div class="lesson-header">
          <h2>10. Building Blocks</h2>
          <button class="lesson-toggle" data-action="click->learn-progress#toggle" data-lesson="lesson-10" data-learn-progress-target="toggleBtn">
            <span class="toggle-check"></span><span class="toggle-text">Mark as complete</span>
          </button>
        </div>
        <p>
          Functions are reusable recipes. Define them with <code>fn</code>:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">let double = fn( x ~> x * 2 ) in double(5)</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">let greet = fn( name ~> 'Hello, ' + name + '!' ) in greet('Elo')</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          The arrow <code>~></code> means "takes this, produces that." Simple!
        </p>
        <p>
          Functions can take multiple inputs:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">let add = fn( a, b ~> a + b ) in add(3, 4)</pre>
        </div>
        <p class="lesson-tip">
          <strong>Read the arrow:</strong> <code>fn( x ~> x * 2 )</code> reads as "a function that takes x and produces x times 2."
          More on <a href={url('/docs#lambdas')}>lambdas</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="lesson" id="lesson-11" data-learn-progress-target="lesson">
        <div class="lesson-header">
          <h2>11. Piping It Through</h2>
          <button class="lesson-toggle" data-action="click->learn-progress#toggle" data-lesson="lesson-11" data-learn-progress-target="toggleBtn">
            <span class="toggle-check"></span><span class="toggle-text">Mark as complete</span>
          </button>
        </div>
        <p>
          Sometimes you want to chain operations. The pipe operator <code>|></code> makes it readable:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">upper(trim('  hello  '))</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          With pipes, the same code reads left-to-right:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">'  hello  ' |> trim |> upper</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          It's like a conveyor belt: data flows from left to right, getting transformed at each step.
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">'  elo is fun  ' |> trim |> upper |> length</pre>
        </div>
        <p class="lesson-tip">
          <strong>Assembly line:</strong> Each step transforms the data and passes it to the next. No nested parentheses, just a clean flow.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="lesson" id="lesson-12" data-learn-progress-target="lesson">
        <div class="lesson-header">
          <h2>12. Transforming Lists</h2>
          <button class="lesson-toggle" data-action="click->learn-progress#toggle" data-lesson="lesson-12" data-learn-progress-target="toggleBtn">
            <span class="toggle-check"></span><span class="toggle-text">Mark as complete</span>
          </button>
        </div>
        <p>
          Now that you know arrays and functions, let's combine them! The <code>map</code> function
          applies a transformation to every item in a list:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">map([1, 2, 3], fn(x ~> x * 2))</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">map(['hello', 'world'], fn(s ~> upper(s)))</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          Want only certain items? Use <code>filter</code> with a predicate (a function that returns true/false):
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">filter([1, 2, 3, 4, 5], fn(x | x > 2))</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          Need to combine all items into one value? That's <code>reduce</code>:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">reduce([1, 2, 3, 4], 0, fn(sum, x ~> sum + x))</pre>
        </div>
        <p class="lesson-tip">
          <strong>The pattern:</strong> <code>map</code> transforms each item, <code>filter</code> keeps some items,
          <code>reduce</code> combines all items into one.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="lesson" id="lesson-13" data-learn-progress-target="lesson">
        <div class="lesson-header">
          <h2>13. Checking Lists</h2>
          <button class="lesson-toggle" data-action="click->learn-progress#toggle" data-lesson="lesson-13" data-learn-progress-target="toggleBtn">
            <span class="toggle-check"></span><span class="toggle-text">Mark as complete</span>
          </button>
        </div>
        <p>
          Sometimes you just want to ask a question about a list. Does <em>any</em> item match?
          Do <em>all</em> items match? Elo has functions for that:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">any([1, 2, 3], fn(x | x > 2))</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">all([1, 2, 3], fn(x | x > 0))</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          Real-world example: are all prices reasonable?
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">let prices = [10, 25, 5, 30] in all(prices, fn(p | p < 100))</pre>
        </div>
        <p class="lesson-tip">
          <strong>Predicate shorthand:</strong> Notice <code>fn(x | x > 0)</code>? The <code>|</code> means
          "such that"—it's a predicate that returns true or false.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="lesson" id="lesson-14" data-learn-progress-target="lesson">
        <div class="lesson-header">
          <h2>14. Handling Nulls</h2>
          <button class="lesson-toggle" data-action="click->learn-progress#toggle" data-lesson="lesson-14" data-learn-progress-target="toggleBtn">
            <span class="toggle-check"></span><span class="toggle-text">Mark as complete</span>
          </button>
        </div>
        <p>
          Sometimes data is missing. Elo represents this with <code>null</code>:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">null</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">isNull(null)</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          The <code>|</code> operator provides a fallback when something is null:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">null | 'default value'</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">let x = null in x | 0</pre>
        </div>
        <p class="lesson-tip">
          <strong>Safe defaults:</strong> The <code>|</code> operator is your friend when dealing with
          optional data. It's like saying "use this, or if it's null, use that instead."
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="lesson" id="lesson-15" data-learn-progress-target="lesson">
        <div class="lesson-header">
          <h2>15. Time Ranges</h2>
          <button class="lesson-toggle" data-action="click->learn-progress#toggle" data-lesson="lesson-15" data-learn-progress-target="toggleBtn">
            <span class="toggle-check"></span><span class="toggle-text">Mark as complete</span>
          </button>
        </div>
        <p>
          Remember dates from lesson 6? Let's check if a date falls within a range.
          Elo has special keywords for common boundaries:
        </p>
        <div class="lesson-example" data-action="click->doc#tryExample">
          <pre class="example-code">TODAY in SOW .. EOW</pre>
        </div>
        <p>
          <code>SOW</code> = Start of Week, <code>EOW</code> = End of Week. There are more:
        </p>
